    <!-- PlaceHolder tag prevents inline radmenu.ClientID code below clashing with Utility.EnsureScriptManager(this); -->
    <script>

        $(document).ready(function () {
            giveAllMenuLinksAUniqueIdentifier();
            $(".rmLink").on("keydown", setSpacebarToOpenMenus);
        });

        function giveAllMenuLinksAUniqueIdentifier() {
            //Give all menu items a unique attribute value so that I can identify them when spacebar is clicked. Same 'menunumber' attribute is set in .aspx code on menu items.
            var index = 0;
            $(".telerik_main_menu li.rmItem a.rmLink").each(function (index) {
                $(this).attr("menunumber", index);
            });
        }

        function setSpacebarToOpenMenus(e) {
            //Open submenus on spacebar press. 
            var theKey = e.which;
            if (theKey == 32) { // 32 is keycode for spacebar. 
                var menuNumber = $(this).attr("menunumber");
                var menu = $find("ctl00_ContentPlaceHolder1_ctl01_radmenu");
                var menuItem = menu.findItemByAttribute("menunumber", menuNumber);
                var submenuItems = menuItem.get_items();
                if (submenuItems.get_count() > 0) {
                    if (menuItem.get_isOpen() == false) {
                        menuItem.open();
                        e.preventDefault();
                    };
                };
            };
        };

        function ClickItem(menu, args) {
            //Event set in OnClientItemClicking="ClickItem";
            //When user clicks (presses Enter key) a menu item, if submenu is not open, then open it; otherwise navigate to the item's link. 
            var item = args.get_item();
            var submenuItems = item.get_items();
            if (submenuItems.get_count() > 0) {
                //If submenu is closed, then open it; otherwise click the menu item link. 
                if (item.get_isOpen() == false) {
                    args.set_cancel(true); //Cancel the default click action so that it doesn't trigger the menu item's navigation link.
                    item.open();
                }
                else {
                    if (typeof item.redirectToLink == 'undefined') {
                        item.redirectToLink = true;
                        item.click();
                    } else {
                        delete item.redirectToLink;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

    </script>

role="main" id="maincontent" class="sectionhome" tabindex="-1"><div class="col-md-9 col-md-9 col-md-push-3"><div id="subpage_content" role="main"><h1>Coronavirus/COVID-19 Updates for the UIC International Community</h1><div class="ptl_page"><div class="ptl_col_1"><div class="ptl_portlet_vertical"><div class="ptl_top_portlet" style="display:none;"></div><div id="ctl00_ContentPlaceHolder1_ctl07_divContent"><p><span style="font-family: Tahoma;">This page consolidates information regarding coronavirus/COVID-19 for the UIC international community as it relates to immigration status, travel guidance, support resources, frequently asked questions (FAQs) and more. For the latest news and information regarding the UIC response to COVID-19, please visit <a href="http://" target="_blank">today.uic.edu/coronavirus</a>.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma;">Updated: April 9, 2020<br>
</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma;"><strong>Is UIC&rsquo;s </strong><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal">Office of International Services open during the COVID-19
pandemic?<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight:bold"><br>
</span></strong>In
response to federal and state government recommendations regarding size limits
for group gatherings, the Office of International Services has moved all
services online, effective immediately, March 17. Our office in SSB will be
closed to visitors until further notice, but our services remain available.
Read the <a href="http://" target="_blank">full
announcement</a> including information on how the UIC international community can
connect with us for advising, document processing and workshops.<strong>&nbsp;</strong>Contact OIS
at (312) 996-3121 or <a href="mailto:ois@uic.edu">ois@uic.edu</a>, Monday through
Friday, 8:30 a.m. to 5 p.m.</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma;">I would like
to make an appointment with an OIS Advisor. How can I do that?<br>
</span></strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma;">OIS
Advisors are available for phone and video appointments during our regular
business hours, 8:30 a.m. to 5:00 p.m., Monday through Friday. Please contact
OIS at (312) 996-3121 or <a href="mailto:ois@uic.edu">ois@uic.edu</a> to request a
phone or video appointment. Include your name, UIN (if available), phone number
and preferred meeting time and we will respond with details on how to connect.</span></p>
<p><strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">I need to submit an immigration document request to OIS.
How can I do that?<br>
</span></strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Current international students, scholars and
employees can submit immigration document requests via email to </span><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><a href="mailto:ois@uic.edu">ois@uic.edu</a></span><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">.
In your message, please include your full name, UIN and attach all relevant
completed forms and supporting documents. </span></p>
<p><strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">I need to collect a document from OIS. How can I do that?<br>
</span></strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">An OIS Advisor will contact you via email
when your request has been processed and your immigration document is ready for
shipment. This email will include details on your shipping options for the
document. Please note that international shipments to some countries are
significantly delayed due to circumstances beyond the control of OIS. Please
see the </span><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><a href="http://" target="_blank">UPS Global Novel Coronavirus Update .pdf</a></span><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"> for a summary of in-country shipping conditions. </span></p>
<ul>
    <li><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><a href="#InformationForInternationalStudents"><strong>Information for International Students</strong></a></span></li>
    <li><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><a href="#InformationForJ-1ExchangeVisitorScholars"><strong>Information for J-1 Exchange Visitor Scholars</strong></a></span></li>
    <li><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><a href="#InformationForInternationalEmployeesAndDepartments"><strong>Information for International Employees and Departments</strong></a></span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">
</span></p>

<h2 id="InformationForInternationalStudents">Information for International Students</h2>
<p class="" style="background: white none repeat scroll 0% 0%;"><span style="color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma;">I would prefer to stay in the U.S. for now. What should I do?</span></strong></span></p>
<ul type="disc">
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Maintain full-time enrollment. If you need to drop a course that would take you below full-time, consult an OIS advisor prior to dropping the course.</span></li>
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Know that your F-1 SEVIS record will remain active (i.e. you will maintain status) while you study full-time online. Participate fully in online or alternative learning as provided by your instructors.</span></li>
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">If you are participating in CPT-authorized internship/practicum/fieldwork, consult with your employer/supervisor to ensure that learning objectives can still be met. If learning objectives cannot be met within the parameters of your current CPT authorization, consult with your academic advisor and OIS immediately for guidance.</span></li>
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">If you are participating in a lab course through a health sciences college, read messages from your dean regarding alternate schedules for clinical rotations and non-clinical courses.</span></li>
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">If your situation changes and you need to leave the U.S. at a later date, connect with an OIS advisor for guidance.</span></li>
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Continue to utilize <a href="http://links.illinois.edu/f/a/I_fa2l9c2YE6GIdzfLItaA~~/AAMFlAA~/RgRgT9T8P0QhaHR0cHM6Ly90b2RheS51aWMuZWR1L2Nvcm9uYXZpcnVzVwNzcGNCCgAp_E9tXhd_K1pSDmFob2JhbkB1aWMuZWR1WAQAAAAE" target="_blank">uic.edu/coronavirus</a> as the most up-to-date and complete source of news, policy and resources regarding UIC&rsquo;s response to coronavirus/COVID-19.</span></li>
</ul>
<p class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>I plan to leave the U.S. and finish the semester online. What should I do?</strong></span></p>
<ul type="disc">
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Maintain full-time enrollment. If you need to drop a course that would take you below full-time, consult an OIS advisor prior to dropping the course.</span></li>
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Know that your F-1 SEVIS record will remain active (i.e. you will maintain status) while you study full-time online. Participate fully in online or alternative learning as provided by your instructors.</span></li>
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Ensure that you will be able to access your instructor&rsquo;s chosen online learning platforms (Blackboard, WebEx, Zoom, etc.) from abroad. Inability to participate in online learning due to Wi-Fi or firewall issues could result in a failing grade.</span></li>
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">If you are participating in a CPT-authorized internship/practicum/fieldwork, consult with an OIS Advisor immediately for guidance on how to update your SEVIS record.</span></li>
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">If you are participating in a lab course through a health sciences college, read messages from your dean regarding alternate schedules for clinical rotations and non-clinical courses. If you are unable to meet learning objectives as a result of your departure, reach out to an OIS Advisor for guidance on how to update your SEVIS record.</span></li>
    <li class="" style="color: rgb(54, 54, 54);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma; font-size: 16px; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Continue to utilize <a href="http://links.illinois.edu/f/a/I_fa2l9c2YE6GIdzfLItaA~~/AAMFlAA~/RgRgT9T8P0QhaHR0cHM6Ly90b2RheS51aWMuZWR1L2Nvcm9uYXZpcnVzVwNzcGNCCgAp_E9tXhd_K1pSDmFob2JhbkB1aWMuZWR1WAQAAAAE" target="_blank">uic.edu/coronavirus</a> as the most up-to-date and complete source of news, policy and resources regarding UIC&rsquo;s response to coronavirus/COVID-19. </span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><br>
I plan to leave the U.S., but won&rsquo;t be able to continue my studies online. What should I do?</strong></span>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><span style="font-weight: normal;">If you leave the U.S., but know that you cannot complete your studies online</span></strong> please consult with your academic advisor and OIS prior to complete the Leave of Absence process prior to departure. The late drop deadline for undergraduate students has been moved from March 20 to April 3.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>Will my F-1 SEVIS record and I-20 remain valid if I return home for the remainder of the spring semester and possibly for the summer as well?</strong><br>
<a href="http://links.illinois.edu/f/a/Hg_alqe_RM_8EAOv4-rF8A~~/AAMFlAA~/RgRgT9T8P0QWaHR0cHM6Ly9iaXQubHkvMlFpY2xSMFcDc3BjQgoAKfxPbV4XfytaUg5haG9iYW5AdWljLmVkdVgEAAAABA~~" target="_blank">F-1 international students can temporarily study online full-time</a> and remain active in SEVIS (i.e. maintain status). The Student and Exchange Visitor Program (SEVP) subsequently <a href="http://links.illinois.edu/f/a/ydI8RoTaTOyplKT00NhCIw~~/AAMFlAA~/RgRgT9T8P0RiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaWNlLmdvdi9zaXRlcy9kZWZhdWx0L2ZpbGVzL2RvY3VtZW50cy9Eb2N1bWVudC8yMDIwL0Nvcm9uYXZpcnVzJTIwR3VpZGFuY2VfMy4xMy4yMC5wZGZXA3NwY0IKACn8T21eF38rWlIOYWhvYmFuQHVpYy5lZHVYBAAAAAQ~" target="_blank">clarified</a> that this is true whether or not the student remains in the U.S. or leaves the U.S. and takes the classes from elsewhere. However, SEVP also stated that this temporary provision is only in effect for the duration of the emergency and is subject to change.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><span style="font-weight: normal;">As an F-1 international student you must be prepared to return to in-person classes at the end of this period of emergency online instruction in response to the coronavirus/COVID-19.</span></strong><strong> </strong>Currently, online instruction extends through the spring semester only. <strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Additionally, if you are considering travel outside the U.S., you must accept that, within the current environment, there is no guarantee you will be able to return to the U.S. according to your plans.</span></strong> </span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>Will I still be able to apply for OPT if I leave the U.S.?<br>
</strong><strong><span style="font-weight: normal;">You must be physically present in the U.S. in order to submit an application for optional practical training (OPT). Currently, if an F-1 student is absent from the U.S. for five months or more, they must apply for a new I-20 and F-1 visa in order to return and resume studies. Students return to the U.S. on a new I-20 and F-1 visa and then graduate in less than a year may not be eligible to apply for OPT.&nbsp; </span></strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>I&rsquo;m undecided about staying or leaving. What should I consider?</strong></span><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><span style="font-weight: normal;"><br>
</span></strong><span style="font-weight: normal;">Additional considerations for those leaving the U.S. for online study or personal temporary travel</span> include:</span>
</p>
<p class=""><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma;">As noted by the </span><a href="http://links.illinois.edu/f/a/6-rEAw3TmXE73DOLjCWZhA~~/AAMFlAA~/RgRgT9T8P0Q-aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2RjLmdvdi9jb3JvbmF2aXJ1cy8yMDE5LW5jb3YvdHJhdmVsZXJzL2luZGV4Lmh0bWxXA3NwY0IKACn8T21eF38rWlIOYWhvYmFuQHVpYy5lZHVYBAAAAAQ~" target="_blank">CDC website</a>, travel to the U.S. from China, Iran and most of Europe is currently restricted. There is no indication as to when these restrictions will be lifted, and countries can be added to this list without prior warning.</span></p>
<p class=""><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma;">Visa services at many U.S. embassies and consulates abroad have been significantly impacted by coronavirus/COVID-19. Before departure, check the </span><a href="http://links.illinois.edu/f/a/FEXC71HI7amwbKrGJKfbaA~~/AAMFlAA~/RgRgT9T8P0RmaHR0cHM6Ly90cmF2ZWwuc3RhdGUuZ292L2NvbnRlbnQvdHJhdmVsL2VuL3RyYXZlbGFkdmlzb3JpZXMvQ09WSUQtMTktQ291bnRyeS1TcGVjaWZpYy1JbmZvcm1hdGlvbi5odG1sVwNzcGNCCgAp_E9tXhd_K1pSDmFob2JhbkB1aWMuZWR1WAQAAAAE" target="_blank">U.S. Department of State website</a> for the status of services at the U.S. Embassy or Consulate nearest you.</span></p>
<p class=""><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><span style="font-family: Tahoma;">Upon return to UIC, you may be subject to self-isolation recommendations regardless of symptoms. Please consult </span><a href="http://links.illinois.edu/f/a/I_fa2l9c2YE6GIdzfLItaA~~/AAMFlAA~/RgRgT9T8P0QhaHR0cHM6Ly90b2RheS51aWMuZWR1L2Nvcm9uYXZpcnVzVwNzcGNCCgAp_E9tXhd_K1pSDmFob2JhbkB1aWMuZWR1WAQAAAAE" target="_blank">uic.edu/coronavirus</a> for current campus guidance.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>Does CampusCare cover treatment for coronavirus/COVID-19?<br>
</strong>CampusCare covers treatment for coronavirus/COVID-19 in the same way it does all other illnesses. If you have CampusCare you can review the plan's <a href="https://campuscare.uic.edu/benefits/" target="_blank" title="https://campuscare.uic.edu/benefits/">summary of benefits</a> on their website. Students who are feeling ill or suspect that they could have coronavirus/COVID-19 should first call their in network provider, Family Medicine at (312) 996-2901, to speak with a medical professional. Note that receiving care from an out of network hospital may not be covered at the same rate as in network providers. Students with additional questions about CampusCare coverage can contact CampusCare directly at <a href="mailto:cchealth@uic.edu" target="_blank">cchealth@uic.edu</a>. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">
<strong><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Can international students work their on-campus
job remotely?<br>
</span></strong><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Yes. Per the <a href="http://" target="_blank">Student and Exchange Visitor Program (SEVP) COVID-19 FAQ</a> if the current on-campus
employment opportunity has transitioned to remote work or the employment can be
done through remote means, students may continue to engage in on-campus
employment remotely. Schools should be able to explain how the students are
providing services associated with the employment while not at the location of
the employer.</span></span></p>
<p><strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Can international students financially impacted by
coronavirus/COVID-19 get authorization to work off-campus in order to earn
additional income?<br>
</span></strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">F-1 students who experience a significant and
unexpected change to their academic funding source as a result of circumstances
beyond their control (e.g. natural disaster, death in the family, global
financial crisis) may be eligible to apply for Severe Economic Hardship
off-campus employment authorization. While this benefit was in place before
coronavirus/COVID-19 it is our understanding that students financially impacted
by coronavirus/COVID-19 will be considered. However, this should not be
considered as an immediate financial solution as applications must be approved
by USCIS, a process which under normal circumstances takes months.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>Will USCIS issue Special Student Relief work authorizations
in response to coronavirus/COVID-19?<br>
</strong><a href="http://" target="_blank">Special Student Relief (SSR)</a> is the suspension of certain regulatory requirements for
F-1 students from parts of the world experiencing emergent circumstances. In the
past SSR has included expedited employment authorization documents for
off-campus work. So far the U.S. government has not discussed SSR in response
to the COVID-19 pandemic.</span><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><br style="mso-special-character:line-break">
<br style="mso-special-character:line-break">
</strong>
</span></p>

<h2 id="InformationForJ-1ExchangeVisitorScholars">Information for J-1 Exchange Visitor Scholars</h2>
<p><strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">How can a J-1 Exchange Visitor Scholar report an additional site of activity?<br>
</span></strong><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">J-1 Exchange Visitors requesting additional sites of activity or intending to conduct program activity at off-campus locations (that OIS is not already aware of) will still need advance approval from OIS. Scholars and departments may reach out to any OIS advisor directly prior to the additional activity taking place for next steps.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>How can a J-1 Exchange Visitor Scholar request a program extension or travel signature?<br>
</strong>OIS will accept scanned copies of the documents when requesting travel signatures and program extension until further notice. Departments and/or scholars should provide the original signed copies via campus mail to follow. Please note for travel signature requests, submission of the original DS-2019 is temporarily not required. We will reprint the document and arrange delivery by mail.</span></p>
<p>
</p>

<h2 id="InformationForInternationalEmployeesAndDepartments">Information for International Employees and Departments<strong><br>
</strong></h2>
<br>
<style>
    &lt;!--
    /* Font Definitions */
    @font-face
    {font-family:"Cambria Math";
    panose-1:2 4 5 3 5 4 6 3 2 4;

    {font-family:Calibri;
    panose-1:2 15 5 2 2 2 4 3 2 4;

<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>Can international employees telecommute (work from home)?<br>
</strong>In most cases, yes, international employees may telecommute but we ask that departments provide OIS with the home address that will be used for work prior to the start. For <strong>H-1B and E-3</strong> employees, it is critical that departments provide OIS with the home address being used for work prior to the start of telecommuting because a new DOL Labor Condition Application (LCA) may be required. Please contact OIS for guidance. No USCIS nor DOL action is required for <strong>TN and O-1</strong> employees, however, this could change if telecommuting becomes a long-term need. Stay tuned. <strong>Individuals working at UIC on an OPT or STEM OPT authorization hosted by another school</strong> should reach out to that school for guidance on how to report changes in work location.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>Can an employer stop paying or &ldquo;bench&rdquo; an international employee due to a reduction in services needed?<br>
</strong>No, employers must continue to pay H-1B and E-3 employees their salary or wage as listed on the Labor Condition Application (LCA) even if the employee is in &ldquo;non-productive status&rdquo;, and employers must continue to pay TN and O-1 employees pursuant to the conditions of the petition previously approved by the Department of Homeland Security.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>What should the department do if an international employee wants to take an extended HR-approved unpaid leave in response to coronavirus/COVID-19?<br>
</strong>Please reach out to OIS for guidance. We will provide details on how to best manage the immigration record depending on length of the leave and whether or not the individual will remain in the U.S. or travel abroad. Contact OIS at (312) 996-3121 or <a href="mailto:ois@uic.edu">ois@uic.edu</a>. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>What should the department do if an international employee needs to make a material change to their position as a result of coronavirus/COVID-19?</strong></span><span style="font-family: Tahoma;"><br>
Materials changes to H-1B, E-3, O-1 and TN positions include full-time to part-time status, changes in title, and other material changes. These types of changes require OIS to file an amendment with USCIS. Additional monitoring of hours may be required. Please consult with an OIS Advisor to determine if a change to a position requires an amendment to be filed with the USCIS.</span><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"> <strong><span style="font-size: 12pt;"></span></strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><span style="font-size: 12pt;">What should a department do if an international resigns of their own accord as result of coronavirus/COVID-19?</span></strong></span><br>
<span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><span style="font-size: 12pt;"></span></strong></span><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><span style="font-size: 12pt;"></span></strong><span style="font-size: 12pt;">Please submit a Departure Verification Form (DVF) to OIS.</span><strong><span style="font-size: 12pt;"></span></strong></span><br>
<span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><span style="font-size: 12pt;"></span></strong></span></p>
<p>
<span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong><span style="font-size: 12pt;"> </span><span style="font-size: 12pt;">How should departments advise international employees who are considering a trip abroad?<br>
</span></strong><span style="font-size: 12pt;">First a foremost, international employees can always consult with OIS advisors regarding their decision to travel internationally during the coronavirus/COVID-19 pandemic. On </span><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=1364777">Monday, March 9</a></span><span style="font-size: 12pt;"> OIS shared a message with the UIC international community in which we strongly discouraged all international students, scholars and employees from traveling outside the U.S. in the near future and that it is not possible to guarantee that individuals will be able to return to the U.S. according to their plans. Our guidance remains the same although we understand that the decision to travel at this point is extremely personal. Those considering international travel with the intention of returning to the U.S. should check their documents before departure and plan for any necessary updates. Visa services at U.S. Embassies and Consulates abroad have been significantly impacted and in many cases suspended due to coronavirus/COVID-19. The </span><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><a href="https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/traveladvisories/COVID-19-Country-Specific-Information.html">U.S. Department of State</a></span><span style="font-size: 12pt;"> has a list COVID-19 specific country information. Travel restrictions continue to be announced limiting entry to countries across the globe. The </span><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><a href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/index.html">U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)</a></span><span style="font-size: 12pt;"> maintains a list of current restrictions on travel to the U.S. Those who are successful in returning to the U.S. may be subject to self-isolation/quarantine before returning to campus. Please follow campus guidance as posted on </span><span style="font-size: 12pt;"><a href="https://today.uic.edu/coronavirus">today.uic.edu/coronavirus</a></span><span style="font-size: 12pt;">.</span></span></p>
<p style="background-position: 0% 0%; background-repeat: repeat; background-attachment: scroll; background-image: none; background-size: auto; background-origin: padding-box; background-clip: border-box;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>Has USCIS announced any suspensions to their processing services related to employment petitions?</strong></span><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(32, 31, 30);"><br>
</span><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);">Yes, on March 20 U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) <a href="https://www.uscis.gov/working-united-states/temporary-workers/uscis-announces-temporary-suspension-premium-processing-all-i-129-and-i-140-petitions-due-coronavirus-pandemic">announced</a></span><span style="font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"> the immediate and temporary suspension of Premium Processing service of all Form I-129 petitions due to Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19), including cap-exempt petitioners such as UIC.&nbsp;Specifically, effective immediately, USCIS will not accept any new requests for Premium Processing of I-129 nonimmigrant petitions, which includes but is not limited to the H-1B and O-1&nbsp;categories.&nbsp;It is expected that any Premium Processing requests received and accepted prior to March 20, 2020 will continue to be processed. If you have case-specific questions regarding how this may impact a matter currently being processed with our office, please contact an OIS advisor. As always, we will immediately notify our colleagues in human resources roles once USCIS has provided any update regarding Premium Processing.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Tahoma; color: rgb(89, 89, 89);"><strong>
</strong></span></p>
